This paper is primarily focused on the design and implementation of a messaging system that provides strong anonymity guarantees. As such, it is likely to be classified under the category of "Computer Science - Cryptography and Security" (cs.CR). Additionally, the paper discusses the scalability of the system, which involves distributed computing and networking concepts, making it relevant to the categories of "Computer Science - Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing" (cs.DC) and "Computer Science - Networking and Internet Architecture" (cs.NI). The paper also discusses techniques for handling server failure and churn, which are relevant to the category of "Computer Science - Data Structures and Algorithms" (cs.DS). Finally, the paper discusses the practical implications of the system, including its potential use in microblogging and private messaging applications, making it relevant to the category of "Computer Science - Systems and Control" (cs.SY).
